Thanks to @RayHudson and @PhilSchoen for the passion, the insight, the humour, & for supporting this account. Thanks also to everyone else at beIN & GolTV who brought us these games, & to the "fancy machines" that allowed us to rewind & capture every detail. We'll miss it.

As La Liga comes to a close on beIN, there are tears the size of pineapple chunks, but when we look back over nearly 12 years & over 3000 tweets, we can all go Barry White disco celebrating the magisterial poetry of the one & only¬†@RayHudson. It wasn't La Liga: it was¬†@RayHudson.
"So many great players for El Cholo Simeone and his pressure made diamonds here today."

"Shakespearean dramas, and all the twists and turns ... Su√°rez alone won 19 points in games that his goals have won ... it's Su√°rez who made the difference, but the manager was Ben Hur behind the chariot."
Atl√©tico win the title. "Luis Suavecito comes through ... celebrations taking place, going absolutely bonkers ... the Atl√©ti fans."

2-1, Real Madrid, Modriƒá. "Golazo! Golazo from the Croatian sensation again. But it's Benzema that sets the table and still breathes life into Los Blancos. They're dead, they're buried? Nah! The resuscitator comes out."
"Sands of time going through the hourglass just too quickly after Benzema was cool as a greyhound's nose with that finish."
1-1, Real Madrid, Benzema. "This one is executed with pure prejudice and prettiness ... the coolness of Karim!"
1-2, Atl√©tico Madrid, Su√°rez. "He is Euclid here. He gets his angles down magnificently and that's cool as a bomb disposal expert."
On the disallowed Benzema goal: "I told you Phil, it's gonna come down to the pixels, baby."
Real Madrid vs. Villareal; Real Valladolid vs. Atl√©tico Madrid.
0-1, Nacho. "Great desire & great execution by Nacho of all people. Casemiro sends a flamethrower across ... and he is there to just kiss this one home."
Athletic Bilbao vs. Real Madrid.

1-4, Benzema, after Rui Silva error. "Magisterial from Benzema. Cooler than Zidane & that takes some doing. The quickness & the calibration of Benzema. He's already taken a dozen freeze-frame pictures in the French cerebral crystal ball in his head & plays it into the empty net."
1-3, Odriozola; Hazard assist. "Substitutions having a party here. Odriozola coming in with the intimidating directness of a torpedo here. Carlos Alberto style in the World Cup in 1970!"

1-2, Molina. "There's a lot of snap, crackle, pop going on around this. This one is saved but beautifully detonated when it falls into Molina's compass ... just a mop-up operation for Molina. Good hit. Good save. Sweet finish."

0-2, Rodrygo. "He's got options ... but Rodrygo says: I see ya, I don't need ya. Makes that space with the little touch to the right-hand side, and that is theodolite accuracy ... mutant fly's-eye vision, but great skill to drive this one home."

0-1, Modriƒá. "Slotted home. Zoom lenses for eyes, Modriƒá: he takes one picture, right there, with his cerebral camera and then nutmegs Rui Silva. Beautiful and smoother than the back of a spoon with this finish. No blast this."
Granada vs. Real Madrid. (Delayed Ray Hudson!)

FT 3-3. On the Le√≥n goal: "A gentler touch than Gandhi stroking a pussycat. Is it poor defending? Is it poor goalkeeping? It doesn't matter. The tombstone is laid, and it looks like Barcelona are going to need a miracle now to pull La Liga out of their hat."

3-3, Le√≥n. "Barcelona absolutely lackadaisical here. An impossible angle, and an exquisite finish. The touch softer than moonlight through the pines. This is a dagger right into the ... well, I was gonna say beating heart of Barcelona. It stopped beating after half-time."
2-3, Demb√©l√©. "He is as cool as an Arctic blast down your shorts. It's a diamond chandelier of a finish, that's for sure. The finish is, again, smooth as the back of a spoon."

2-2, Morales. "Game drawn level here now & Morales is the cat's pyjamas with the finish. And the bee's knees. It's Messi who gives away; sloppy as a soup sandwich this time from Lionel. The cat's pyjamas, the bee's knees & then the finish from Morales is the moxie of a monkey."
1-2, Melero. "You could sense it coming, this team was playing well and sharp, and Barcelona hitting the snooze button."

0-2, Pedri; Demb√©l√© assist, via Messi. "Just gotta touch it home. I don't know how much of a stumble it is. It's messy. It's messy, it's Messi. Again, smuggles it past his defenders. Ventilates every touch of the ball, Lionel."

0-1, Messi. "How do you nail Jell-O to the ceiling? All the gyroscopes in his incredible footballing brain adjusted & it's cleaner than Neutrogena for the man from Argentina. The zenith angles measured down to the degrees & the minutes & the azimuth angles coordinated, for Leo!"
Levante vs. Barcelona.
2-2, Hazard. "You think this crazy season couldn't get any crazier? Eden Hazard produces the touch that draws this game level."

1-2, Rakitiƒá (pen). "Cool as a polar bear's toenails here ... Talk about pressure making diamonds. With this time left on the clock, Real Madrid'll never be out of this. We've got an unbelievable helter-skelter fifteen minutes ahead of us."
1-1, Asensio; Kroos assist. "Toni picks a beautiful ace out of his hand for Asensio to draw it level. A red carpet pass and it is executed like that Ming guy: merciless! Beautiful finish."

0-1, Fernando. "Cooler than Vladimir Putin on Russian election day here. Take a look at how composed and totally cool he is when it falls to him. Watch this touch. He puts Casemiro on his back like a turtle before firing it home past Courtois."
Real Madrid vs. Sevilla.
2-3, full time. "For the king of the match, it's the GOAT. Lionel Messi: football's silicon chip, with eyes and legs."

2-3, Soler. "It's a Solar hit! One point twenty-one gigawatts! One point twenty-one gigawatts! A magisterial strike. Absolutely brilliant from Carlos. That's hotter than Carlos Santana! Carlos Soler: stupefyingly magnificent to draw this game back and put it on the ledge again."

"You just sense something in your water. In that area, at that angle: that's where the true Stradivarius comes out, in that left foot. Just sensed it, that it was gonna be showtime. Cabaret free kick. Messi as Liza Minnelli."

(Watching replays.) "Well, he couldn't score from the penalty spot; he makes up for it here. And then his pi√®ce de r√©sistance was his free kick, which showed the Messi talent on a level that cloud technology couldn't store."

"The madness of Messi. This is insane talent, where the unexpected becomes the guaranteed. Where the impossible becomes the routine! Minnesota Fats, with his Stradivarius left foot: 8-ball, top pocket. Uses the cushion. Magic. Messi: brilliance on amphetamines again."

1-2, Griezmann. "He says, who's tracking him? Nobody. Again, Griezmann keeps reigniting the defenders' nightmares. Over last few weeks, he's been on the spot & again, Antoine-nets! Cillessen throws the welcome mat down & Antoine Griezmann wipes his feet on it."

1-1, Messi (after penalty saved). "A comedy of errors and a bad mistake by Leo who was very casual in his approach ... Jasper Cillessen reads him all day like Jack and Jill goes up the hill ... Pedri smacks the snot out of this [follow up], and then Messi wipes his nose."

1-0, Paulista. "It's calamity for Barcelona. Free man in the park here after the collision with Ter Stegen ... collisions are gonna happen. I think that's a fair goal. And it's as ugly as a witch's nose with warts on it ... now there's a fire in Barcelona's basement."
Valencia vs. Barcelona.

2-0, Casemiro "Casemiro does it the witching way & just gets a toe to it. Whether or not that's an intentional strike, who the hell knows & who the hell cares if you're a Madridista? I think he's trying to control it Phil, but who knows? He's Brazilian. They do it different ways"

1-0, Milit√£o. "He's been rattling at the latch of brave Osasuna all night long. He executes with extreme prejudice and prettiness. That's a magisterial header, people ... that is fire on ice from the Brazilian ... nothing given in the VAR truck by the boys down by the river."
Real Madrid vs. Osasuna. Delayed Ray Hudson!

1-2, Molina. "Molina magic with this header. The defence of Barcelona goes missing like the kids in The Blair Witch Project, and there's no change for Ter-Spiderman this time. Barcelona are served their heads for not taking advantage of that one-goal lead."
1-1, Mach√≠s. "He recognizes where the chance is and he absolutely kicks this door in."

1-0, Messi; Griezmann assist. "Clairvoyant passing again, they're like dolphins chattering to each other. Antoine turns like a cork in a Chardonnay bottle. Minnesota Fats, 8-ball, bottom pocket. Fabulous pirouette from Antoine, and Messi-nets this time!"
Barcelona vs. Granada.

2-1, Mart√≠nez. "Just a glitterbomb of a header here by I√±igo Mart√≠nez, and where's the defending this time? It's a perfect corner kick by Ibai. He sends this one in with a dozen roses tied around it."
1-1, Saviƒá. "Magisterial from the Montenegro international. Contorts and twists his neck like Linda Blair in The Exorcist. Game back on."

1-0, Berenguer. "√Ålex the Great arrives by stealth. Does it a deflection on its way to Big √Ålex? If it does it's even a better header because he's got to adjust his gyroscope on the fly ... he goes Barry White disco!"
Athletic Bilbao vs. Atl√©tico Madrid.

1-1, Griezmann. "Slippier than an ice cube on an oven top, here. Antoine-nets again! The finish is immaculate. Smoother than a Zamboni from Antoine. This game has got more 'flare' than a 1970s high school reunion. He could shave a mouse in his sleep here Phil."

1-0, Chukwueze. "He stretches this team out like spandex on Miami Beach ... look at the pass. .. the skeleton key comes out ... Jordi Alba cannot keep his feet ... and he is punish'd. He flies through the defence like Han Solo in an asteroid field."
Villareal vs. Barcelona.
@DreCordero All the best! Will miss your commentary.

5-2, Griezmann (pen). "Well, the scoreline will say 5-2, and it has been a wacky game. We've seen all sorts of beautiful goals and absolutely goals that have got the look of a witch's nose with warts on it. A wonderful strike into the bottom corner from Antoine-nets!"

4-2, Ara√∫jo; Messi assist. "Zoom lenses for eyes, Messi. It's a beautiful set-piece goal for Barcelona, that puts the Barcelona faithful into their BarcaLoungers, in relax mode. Messi, as always, fire on ice. Ara√∫jo [header] as cool as an Arctic blast down your shorts."
"The footballing gods flash their blaugrana eyelashes at Leo, and he skips the light fantastic with a bit of fandango thrown in for good measure."

3-1, Messi. "It's Leo using the upright as his reference point, and plays a one-two off of it. Slippier than an ice cube on an oven top. This halo of a footballer, again, tonight looking like a shark that's been in a fish tank for a week, Phil. He's really up for this game."

On the Busquets assist: "That combination is better than Lennon and McCartney, but we've seen it over the decade of this wonderful combination ... they're on a frequency, and they both understand it, like two chattering dolphins."
"Wonderful strike, what a ball from Sergi Busquets ... Dr. Einstein called it the spooky action over distance. He was thinking about Busquets and Messi, I'm sure."

1-0, Messi. "The divine combination, connection, of his eyes to his brain, to his footballing feet. Again, epinephrine in football boots, Phil? You wanna see what pure adrenaline looks like? You just saw it. You just saw what the Invisible Man looks like! Lionel!"
Barcelona vs. Getafe.
HT review: "Real Madrid on top of their game from the first minute, and moved the ball around from the first seconds, and they are looking sharper than Edward Scissorhands tonight."
HT review, second goal: "The NBA: Nacho, to Benz, to Alvaro at the back post."
0-3, Benzema; Casemiro assist. "Benzema, once again, smoother than a Zamboni with his finish, nothing less. A beautifully varnished pass here from Casemiro."

0-2, Odriozola; Benzema assist. "The Karim rises to the top again, with pure French class. Holds, hesitates and guides this heavenly rainbow pass around. He's already taken a dozen freeze-frame pictures in the cerebral camera within his head."
0-1, Benzema (pen). "Well, the creator shows he that can also play solo violin here. He's the man who created the opportunity for Vini ... Benzema's power, placement, is immaculate."
C√°diz vs. Real Madrid.

"I for one will say openly, and without any inhibition that i hope to see mini mighty Eibar return to La Liga if they do go down. They're still in with a chance and they will fight to their last breath."

5-0, Llorente. "[Eibar's] house is on fire. It's been burned down before this goal. [Atl√©tico] can't stop playing their penetrating football. Sad eyes on Jos√© Luis Mendilibar: the 60-year-old starting look as stressed out as a 60-year-old air traffic controller now."

4-0, Llorente. "As I said, this game well put to bed now, and we're watching the Eibar team fall apart like King Louie's temple in the Jungle Book ... look at this pass across the face, Correa splits the defence ... Llorente ties a dozen roses around it."
"This game is put to bed with three hot water bottles now, Phil."

3-0, Carrasco. "It's a clairvoyant pass. Pyrotechnic passing again but then when it falls to Yannick, he latches onto this one like a piranha and he ain't letting go. Spooky action over distance, Einstein called it, Phil, and that's what it gets you. The doctor was right."

1-0, Correa "Lady Luck finally shows her face & flutters her red & white eyelashes at Atl√©tico. Correa believes in the "what if?" Anything can happen at the back post, so let's go for it. Wonderful header on that near post to open up the window of opportunity & Correa crashes in"
Atl√©tico Madrid vs. Eibar.

On Bravo's goalkeeping: "They should be constructing operas about his performance today in Sevilla. This is a magisterial save again ... look at this attack of the space from Claudio Bravo! Demonic in his resistance, & a dozen exorcists couldn't get the demons out of this player"

1-1, Tello. "Tello is sharper than a porcupine's backside with his finish.  Magisterial from Tello. He's gotta adjust all of his gyroscopes here, in the blink of a bee's eye. He keeps it down, he keeps it on target & Oblak just cannot react to it; it's a flash coming back to him"
0-1, Carrasco. "They are busier than a hill of ants coming at Real Betis here. Some wonderful embroidered football from Atl√©tico."
Real Betis vs. Atl√©tico Madrid.

2-1, Mingueza. "It finds its way through to the defender Mingueza whose finish is ... good enough, and brings his team back into the game. The passing has got better as the conditions have got worse, so, figure that out!"

2-0, Kroos free kick. "A man that's playing absolutely out of his skin as he approaches the plateau of his career. The World Cup winner -- he's got zoom lenses for eyes here. Lynx-eye vision from Toni."
1-0, Benzema. "Benzema absolutely pulls a peacock out of his hat. It's a majestic finish from Karim, who again, rises to the top."
Real Madrid vs. Barcelona.  El Cl√°sico!

If the Fed does not pivot, the set-up will be more like 1929. The Fed raised rates in 1929 to squelch financial speculation and then, in 1930, Congress passed Smoot-Hawley, putting 50%+ tariffs on more than 20,000 goods and pushing the global economy into the Great Depression.

As inflation dropped to -15% in June 1921, the Fed lowered interest rates from 7% in May 1921 to 4% in July 1922, tripping the switch for the Roaring Twenties. From August 1921 to September 1929, the Dow Jones Industrial Average compounded at a annual rate of 25%.

If inflation drops below the Fed‚Äôs 2% target and economic activity disappoints, then interest rates are likely to surprise on the low side of expectations next year, ushering in this century‚Äôs rendition of the Roaring Twenties.

Founded in 1913 and challenged by its first bout of serious inflation, the Fed raised interest rates less than two-fold from 4.6% to 7% in 1919-1920. Faced with much lower inflation this time around, the Fed has increased interest rates 16-fold, a serious mistake in our view.

During WWI and the Spanish Flu, supply chain and other shocks pushed inflation to 20%+. At its worst in June 1920, inflation peaked at 24% but then dropped precipitously in one year to -15% in June 1921. We would not be surprised to see broad-based inflation turn negative in 2023

Prior to the Roaring Twenties, the world was at war - WWI - and suffering a pandemic - Spanish Flu. While both had a more serious impact on the global economy, today‚Äôs combination is a strong echo that could result in much lower than expected inflation and a boom in innovation.

If inflation is unwinding, as we believe, then we could be heading back to the future, the Roaring Twenties, the last time several general purpose technologies evolved at the same time: telephone, electricity, and the internal combustion engine. The setup is remarkably similar!

Further downstream, retailers seem to be swimming in inventories which they could be forced to discount aggressively to clear the shelves for holiday merchandise. The surprise could be deflation in the CPI and PCE deflator by year-end.

In the pipeline, inflation is turning into deflation. One of the best inflation gauges, the gold price peaked more than two years ago in August 2020 at $2075 and has dropped ~15%. Lumber prices have dropped more than 60%, copper -30%, iron ore -60%, DRAM -46%, and crude oil -35%.

The Fed has raised the Fed funds rate 10-fold from 0.25% to 2.50%, five times Volcker‚Äôs 2-fold increase from 10% to 20% in the early ‚Äò80s when consumers and businesses had been adjusting to inflation for 10-15 years. In contrast, today they are in shock. Housing is unraveling.

Not ‚Äòtil Volcker took charge in 1979, 15 years after the Vietnam War and Great Society began, did the Fed attack inflation decisively. In contrast, faced with a two year supply-related inflation shock, Powell is using Volcker‚Äôs sledgehammer and, I believe, making a mistake.

At Jackson Hole, Chairman Powell invoked Volcker‚Äôs name twice directly, twice indirectly. Today‚Äôs COVID-supply-shock inflation is nothing like the ‚Äò70s inflation that started with ‚Äúguns and butter‚Äù in 1964, and accelerated after Nixon ended the gold-exchange standard in 1971.

The Fed is basing monetary policy decisions on lagging indicators: employment and core inflation. Leading inflation indicators like gold and copper are flagging the risk of deflation. Even the oil price has dropped more than 35% from its peak, erasing most of the gain this year.

In the last two weeks, while the well-regarded JAMA has featured studies that both support and refute the benefits of #psychedelics, @ARKInvest‚Äôs life science analyst, @PierceARK, is helping us size the potential market. Thank you @C_Angermayer for your support and inspiration!
We would not be surprised to see new and used car prices unwind fairly dramatically, threatening auto residual values and the $1+ trillion in auto credit in the US during the next year.

To avoid mass transit, consumers hoarded cars in 2020-21. While used car prices were rising, they were enjoying ‚Äúinventory profits‚Äù and probably were in no rush to sell after the crisis. Now prices are falling, threatening them with inventory losses, so they are likely to sell.
